1
00:00:04,849 --> 00:00:07,094
In the previous lesson,

2
00:00:07,094 --> 00:00:10,349
you saw how histograms and bar charts can be adapted into

3
00:00:10,349 --> 00:00:15,855
bivariate plots by changing the count axis to indicate the mean of a second variable.

4
00:00:15,855 --> 00:00:20,280
We can follow a similar approach for heat maps and clustered bar charts,

5
00:00:20,280 --> 00:00:24,554
to change them from bivariate plots into multivariate plots.

6
00:00:24,554 --> 00:00:27,890
For example, let's take this heat map

7
00:00:27,890 --> 00:00:31,390
regarding shots made over a series of basketball games.

8
00:00:31,390 --> 00:00:36,215
X and y positions are relative to the basket which is at the origin.

9
00:00:36,215 --> 00:00:38,095
In this multivariate plot,

10
00:00:38,094 --> 00:00:39,969
the color shows the third variable,

11
00:00:39,969 --> 00:00:43,494
how accurate shots were in each region of the court.

12
00:00:43,494 --> 00:00:47,354
Darker colors indicate a higher proportion of shots made.

13
00:00:47,354 --> 00:00:49,640
You can see that very generally,

14
00:00:49,640 --> 00:00:54,509
the shots that were closer to the basket had a higher chance of making it in.

